"22 ounce bomber into a Goose Island tulip. 1/11/12 bottle date. Small beige head, low retention. Black body. Aroma includes marshmallow, vanilla, coffee, chocolate, bourbon, some alcohol and some of those wafer cookies. Taste follow suit with some molasses notes and brandy. Thick, viscous and rediculously good."
"Pours black and rests beneath a half-inch thick layer of brown, frothy head that resides for a couple of minutes. The aroma is of bourbon, oak, ground coffee, a bit of espresso, chocolate, vanilla, caramel, and a touch of almond and hazelnut towards the end. It tastes of bourbon, vanilla, coffee grounds, hazelnut, oak, maybe some cedar (or other dry wood), some nuts (almond, cashew), and chocolate with a nice roasted malt finish. Mouthfeel is lively, yet thick. It readily coats the mouth, but the carbonation keeps it from leaving a sticky residue. Finish is clean, but I wouldn’t call it dry. Overall, this is an impressive stout. The base beer is wonderful in its own right, and the addition of coffee adds a whole new dimension."
